<h2>HVAC Systems in Pennsylvania</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Pennsylvania's humid continental climate creates substantial heating and cooling demands throughout the year, making efficient HVAC systems essential for comfort and energy cost management. Winter temperatures frequently drop below freezing, with heating degree days ranging from 4,500 in southeastern regions to over 6,500 in northern and mountainous areas. Summers are typically warm and humid, with cooling degree days averaging 800-1,200 annually, creating significant air conditioning loads from June through September.</p>

<p>The state's climate variability requires HVAC systems capable of handling temperature swings from below 0¬∞F in winter to above 90¬∞F in summer, often within the same year. Humidity levels remain relatively high year-round, making dehumidification an important consideration for summer comfort and indoor air quality. These conditions favor heat pump systems in moderate climate zones, while areas with frequent sub-freezing temperatures may benefit from dual-fuel or traditional furnace systems with high-efficiency air conditioning.</p>

<p>Pennsylvania's shoulder seasons (spring and fall) offer opportunities for natural ventilation and reduced HVAC runtime, but the relatively short duration of these mild periods means heating and cooling systems operate extensively throughout the year. Proper system sizing becomes crucial, as oversized equipment will short-cycle during moderate weather, reducing efficiency and comfort while increasing wear on system components.</p>

