<h2>Pennsylvania Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>Pennsylvania offers several attractive incentive programs that significantly improve the financial returns of solar and HVAC investments. The federal Investment Tax Credit remains the most substantial incentive, providing 30% of solar system costs as a tax credit through 2032. This credit applies to the complete solar installation, including equipment, labor, permitting, and interconnection costs, with no cap on the credit amount for residential installations.</p>

<p>Pennsylvania's Solar Alternative Energy Credit (SREC) program provides ongoing revenue for solar system owners by requiring utilities to purchase renewable energy credits. Each 1,000 kWh of solar production generates one SREC, which utilities must purchase to meet renewable energy requirements. SREC prices fluctuate based on market supply and demand, typically ranging from \$25-45 per credit. A typical 7kW residential system generating 8,200 kWh annually would produce approximately 8.2 SRECs worth \$205-370 in additional annual income.</p>

<p>PECO Energy offers several rebate programs for customers in its service territory, including rebates for high-efficiency heat pumps, smart thermostats, and ductless mini-split systems. The utility's Energy Efficiency Rebate Program provides \$300-750 rebates for qualifying HVAC equipment installations, with higher rebates available for ENERGY STAR certified equipment. PECO also offers free energy audits and customized efficiency recommendations for customers considering system upgrades.</p>

<p>Local municipalities and counties occasionally offer additional incentive programs, particularly for energy efficiency improvements. Some Pennsylvania counties participate in Property Assessed Clean Energy (PACE) financing programs, allowing homeowners to finance solar and efficiency improvements through property tax assessments. These programs can provide 100% financing with terms up to 20 years, making upgrades accessible without upfront costs.</p>

<p>The Database of State Incentives for Renewables & Efficiency (DSIRE) maintains current information on all available incentives, as programs can change annually based on funding availability and policy updates. Homeowners should verify current incentive availability and requirements before making investment decisions, as some programs have limited funding or specific eligibility criteria.</p>

